I think we can directly allocate stack memory here, to avoid declaring extra variables on stack
```
typedef struct vec {
    size_t size;       /* Number of elements in the vector. */
    size_t cap;        /* Capacity of the vector. */
    void **data;       /* Heap-allocated storage or refers to stack. */
    void *stack[VEC_DEFAULT_INITCAP]; 
}
```

and pass a hint when init, if the hint is more than VEC_DEFAULT_INITCAP, we can zmalloc directly when `zmalloc+memcpy` later.
```
 vecInit(vec *v, int hint) {
    if (hint <= VEC_DEFAULT_INITCAP) {
        v->data = v->stack;
        v->cap = VEC_DEFAULT_INITCAP;
    } else {
        v->data = zmalloc(sizeof(void*) * hint);
        v->cap = hint;
    }
    v->size = 0;
}
```

other issue, we should use redis style (camel case). vecInit, vecData, vecDestroy

We are defining here a general purpose vector. Note that it might be embedded in structs, beyond stack. As long as t_hash is the only client of this use case maybe it should hold locally something like:
```
/* syntactic sugar for vec with stack of 8 elements */
typedef struct vec8 { vec v; void *stack[8]; } vec8;
static inline vec *vec8Init(vec8 *x) {
    vecInit(&x->v, x->buf, 8);
    return &x->v;
}
```
Once we shall have another use case , we can pass this code to reside in vector.h
